    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Clinton administration's response to the remarks of Sha Zukang, China's chief arms negotiator (news article, May 12), misses the point.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Clinton administration's response to the remarks of Sha Zukang, China's chief arms negotiator (news article, May 12), misses the point.</p>
        <p>It is not whether China will continue to modernize its strategic forces. Of course it will. The point is that the United States' dismissal of China's concerns about missile defense is sure to curtail China's willingness to take part in bilateral and multilateral arms talks of any nature.</p>
        <p>The Clinton administration should devote as much diplomatic energy to reassuring China as it has to its NATO allies and Russia, whose strategic forces ultimately are less susceptible to the defense systems now proposed.</p>
        <p>KENNETH WEISBRODE  London, May 15, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a research associate at the International Institute for Strategic Studies.</p>
      </block>
